message.text:
#Hiragana Master
Say it Together! Basic Japanese Words in Japanese Alphabetical Order.
Today's Word is "MA" MATSURI　#nihongo
日本の単語を五十音順にわかりやすく紹介！「ま」つり（祭り、Festival）http://words.marugotoweb.jp/search_detail.php?id=2022,915&p=1&q=%E7%A5%AD&source=search&lang=en

Festival culture makes a country unique. 
Japanese festivals are often featured by lively dance moves and calls. 
We say "Dancing fool, watching fool: all fools, so let's all dance!"
It is said that there are more than 300,000 festivals in Japan. 
If you ever encounter one by chance while you are here, join and dance along! 

その国の文化が色濃く出るもの、それは「お祭り」。
日本のお祭りは賑やかな踊りや掛け声が特徴的ですね。
「踊る阿呆に見る阿呆、同じ阿呆なら踊らにゃ損損！」
日本にはなんと30万以上のお祭りがあるとか。
幸運にも出くわしたら、なりふり構わずジョインしましょう！

message.text:
“Seri, nazuna, gogyo, hakobe, hotokenoza, suzuna, and suzushiro” 
Is this a spell?? No no, it’s “Seven Spring Herbs.”
「セリ・ナズナ・ゴギョウ・ハコベラ・ホトケノザ・スズナ・スズシロ」
何の呪文？いえいえ、「春の七草（はるのななくさ）」です！

Today is January 7th, a day to eat these seven herbs as a rice porridge!

This custom was introduced from China and then became popular in Japan by Edo period. Its original intention is to protect oneself against evils and invite good luck and longevity by eating the seven-herbs that endured the cold winter because it was said to purge you of noxious vapors.Nowadays, it also means to settle your stomach after eating all the rich, salty foods from the New Year's celebration. 

The seven herbs differ depending on the period and area, but the prayers for the “Nanakusa-gayu　（七草粥、ななくさがゆ）”- good health and peace- hasn't changed. 
Let's eat "Nanakusa-gayu" and have a healthy 2015!

今日は１月７日。
春の七草をお粥にして食べる日です。中国から伝わったこの習慣は、日本では江戸時代に全国に広まったといわれています。七草は、早春にいち早く芽吹くことから悪い気を払うといわれており、無病息災を祈って食べられています。現在では、お正月に飲み食いして疲れた胃を休め、いつもの食事に戻る節目とも言われていますよ！

七草の種類は時代や土地によって違いますが、「今年も元気で平和に暮らせますように」という思いは一緒。
七草粥を食べて今年も元気に！

＜For Your Information＞
Paris (France): Jan.31 [Culinary Demonstrations] Settle your stomach from New Year’s rich dish 
パリ：1/31　[食文化デモンストレーション]　疲れた胃を休ませるやさしい食事！　
http://urx2.nu/fTDG
-------------
<春の七草 “Seven Spring Herbs.”>
Seri (Japanese parsley) / Nazuna (shepherd’s purse) / Gogyo (Jersey cudweed),
Hakobe (common chickweed) / Hotoke no za (henbit) / Suzuna (turnip) / Suzushiro (daikon)

message.text:
「明けましておめでとうございます。旧年中は大変お世話になりました。今年もよろしくお願いいたします。」 
"Happy New Year! Thank you very much for your support and kindness last year. I wish you all the best for this year."

In Japan, we exchange New Year's greeting card called "Nenga-jo（年賀状、ねんがじょう）" with the message like the one above at the beginning of the year, usually in the postcard format.

In the ancient times, people  used to  visit friends and relatives to say "Happy New Year" in person . As time goes by, that practice had been simplified, and the manner of exchanging "Nenga-jo" was established.
Now it is systematized  that we can receive "Nenga-jo" on the very first day of the year if it is dropped into the post during December, and we all are looking forward to checking the mail box on January 1st.!

It gets even more simpified nowadays, and more and more people are exchanging New Year's greetings via e-mail or SNS tools.

Look, We've got a huuuge "Nenga-jo" from Jakarta, Indonesia :）yeah!
日本では、年のはじめに、旧年中の感謝を込めて新年の挨拶をする「年賀状」を出す習慣があります。
最近はメールやＳＮＳで年始の挨拶を行う人も多いですよね！
基金本部も、ジャカルタ・ＪＦミニセミナー参加者のみんなから、特大年賀状をもらいましたよ（＾＾）♪
